
[1]impervious

   IMPER'VIOUS, a. [L. impervius; in and pervius, passable; per and via,
   way.]

   1. Not to be penetrated or passed through; impenetrable; as an
   impervious gulf; an impervious forest.

   2. Not penetrable; not to be pierced by a pointed instrument; as an
   impervious shield.

   3. Not penetrable by light; not permeable to fluids. Glass is pervious
   to light, but impervious to water. Paper is impervious to light. In the
   latter sense only, impervious is synonymous with impermeable.
